dismissalText.commentary: Brendan Taylor b Shoaib Malik 49 (78b 5x4 0x6 104m) SR: 62.82

dismissalComment.html: Big turn to terminate Taylor's resistance. It pithched a foot outside off stump, Taylor went back and was surprised by the sharp turn that saw the ball rush through his bat and pad. Timber! Just before Malik started his run-up, Sarfraz had chirped, "No 7 No 7  boys"

headshotImage.caption: Fawad Alam player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Fawad Alam player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.long: st Sarfaraz Ahmed b Fawad Alam
dismissalText.commentary: Elton Chigumbura st Sarfaraz Ahmed b Fawad Alam 34 (58b 2x4 0x6 73m) SR: 58.62

dismissalComment.html: And it's really bahut aala (very nice) from both the bowler and the 'keeper. Fawad slowed it up, tossed it up a little more, drew the batsman forward before turning it past the bat and Sarfraz did the rest. A useful partnership of 85 runs comes to an end.

What a catch to get your first wicket! Don't trust your fielders, take it yourself, says Rauf. Full in length, on the off stump and is driven low to him and Rauf picks it off his shoe laces in one fluent motion.

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

dismissalComment.html: yorked! Around 130 kmph, full and straight at the off stump, hint of late movement in and Price has a stab and a miss.

headshotImage.caption: Chris Mpofu player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Chris Mpofu player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: Yorked again! Raufed up! This one swung in a bit more than the previous delivery and went past the jab to crash into the off stump. In a nice gesture, the Pakistani fielders ask Wahab Riaz and Rauf to lead them back to the pavilion.

image.caption: Tatenda Taibu
image.longCaption: Tatenda Taibu portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

dismissalComment.html: Wow! Stunning catch at covers. That man Rizwan again. It was poor delivery - short and wide- and Taibu slashed it in the air but Rizwan took off in the air, left hand outstretched and was parallel to the ground when he took it. Watch it in the Youtube. Coming soon, in a computer near you

Williams could have a misty eye now. He has top-edged a pull shot. It was the short one from Riaz - who has shown a penchant to send that delivery now and then - and Williams' pull went awry. Caught at long-leg. Zimbabwe slid further.

dismissalText.commentary: Chamu Chibhabha lbw b Shoaib Malik 1 (2b 0x4 0x6 5m) SR: 50

dismissalComment.html: trapped by a quicker one! That one really zipped through. It landed on a length and seamed on straight, Chibhabha was caught completely by surprise and the ball evaded the intended jab and struck him high on the pad. He was on the back foot but the ball looked high. Zaheer Abbas, on air, reckons it would have gone over.

dismissalText.commentary: Younis Khan c Masakadza b Price 63 (51b 8x4 1x6 70m) SR: 123.52

dismissalComment.html: Masakadza takes a skier. Price went wide of the crease this time, from round the stumps and flighted across a loopy delivery outside off. Younis Khan went down on his knee and attempted a slog-sweep but top edged it towards long-off. Well taken by Masakadza

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

dismissalText.commentary: Khurram Manzoor b Price 50 (73b 6x4 0x6 105m) SR: 68.49

dismissalComment.html: cleans him up. Right after fifty, he went for a sweep and is gone. It was full and on the off stump, too full to play that hard sweep and it went under the bat and on to the off stump. Price is chuffed up; he really wanted Khurram's wicket, had beaten him on a few occasions. And finally does him in with a straighter one.

commentPreTextItems.html: Misbah moves outside leg and Price stops at the release point. The crowd roar while Price has a naughty smile spread across his visage.

commentTextItems.html: again he moves outside leg stump, Price sends in a full toss which is flat-batted over long-off. A white wash. This is the fourth time Pakistan have swept a five-match series.

commentPostTextItems.html: Players from both teams are out on the field, shaking hands and having a chat. Price meets up with Khurram Manzoor  - he had a few words with him in the heat of the battle- and Price taps the youngster's back, says something and both laugh. Great to see.
Hang on for the post-match presentation.

Man of the Match: Younis Khan: "I just wanted to be aggressive today and entertain the crowd. I am looking forward to the Australia series ... we have two or three fast bowlers and a few openers too. The future looks good. It was great to see the crowd turn out, it was great fun."
Masakadza: "In retrospect, may be we should have bowled first today. We have lots to work on in all the three departments of the game. And he says to the crowd, Shukriya Pakistan " (Thanks Pakistan!)

Man of the series: Shoaib Malik : "It has been a great series as we have learned a lot. Especially, our youngsters. We have to improve on our fielding and running between the wickets. Its good for us that the youngsters have performed. Against Australia, we should be getting our seniors back and it's nice to have a good combination. Thanks to the Sheikapura crowd."
And thanks to you gentlemen and ladies for logging on to Cricinfo. This is Sriram Veera, your commentator for the day, saying Alvida. Good night and shab bakhair!

commentTextItems.html: makes room and lofts over mid-off. The scores are level
almost got his man. Misbah went for a slog sweep and got a edge but it doesn't carry to backward point

lands on the off and middle , turns ever so slowly and Misbah tries to turn it to leg side but there is no pace to work with and the ball just rolls in front of him. Price has a big smile- he has really bowled well today, changing his pace constantly and varying the angles
slows up the pace and shifts his line to outside off, pushed to covers
wide down the leg side. 5 more runs now.
goes back to work it to midwicket. Again he wanted to turn it towards square leg,didn't quite get his wrists working well
slower one, on the pads, turned past square leg for a single. How many last-ball singles has Misbah taken? Hmm..!

commentTextItems.html: full and straight and he respects the line and length by defending
steers this length delivery to backward point.
short in length and played towards cover. He wanted to force it through cover point as he is seen practising that shot afterwards.
shifts his line to just outside off and is defended to covers
on the legs and Misbah helps himself to another boundary with a flick
on the off stump line, dabbed to the on side. Price thought it hit the pad first and lets out a stifled appeal

commentTextItems.html: outside off stump, not all that short but Fawad cuts it on the width and forces it away to the point boundary
outside off stump and defended solidly
on the middle and leg, gets off the strike with a nudge behind square leg
on the off stump line, Misbah was beaten in the flight but adjusts to push it out to point. Price lets out a cry of agony
on the middle and leg, worked to midwicket . 16 to win
shout for lbw but he got an inside-edge on it. It was full, hint of shape in and he pushed hard at it

dismissalText.commentary: Hamilton Masakadza c & b Abdur Rauf 5 (13b 0x4 0x6 31m) SR: 38.46

dismissalComment.html: What a catch to get your first wicket! Don't trust your fielders, take it yourself, says Rauf. Full in length, on the off stump and is driven low to him and Rauf picks it off his shoe laces in one fluent motion.

headshotImage.caption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Vusi Sibanda run out (Rizwan Ahmed/Sarfaraz Ahmed) 18 (36b 2x4 0x6 55m) SR: 50

dismissalComment.html: Run out by Rizwan from long leg. It was on the pads, clipped past square leg and they tried to push for the second run. Rizwan moved swiftly to his right, swooped and fired in flat and accurate throw. Sarfraz does the rest. Gone!

image.caption: Tatenda Taibu
image.longCaption: Tatenda Taibu portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

image.caption: Tatenda Taibu
image.longCaption: Tatenda Taibu portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

dismissalText.long: c Rizwan Ahmed b Wahab Riaz
dismissalText.commentary: Tatenda Taibu c Rizwan Ahmed b Wahab Riaz 6 (11b 0x4 0x6 16m) SR: 54.54

dismissalComment.html: Wow! Stunning catch at covers. That man Rizwan again. It was poor delivery - short and wide- and Taibu slashed it in the air but Rizwan took off in the air, left hand outstretched and was parallel to the ground when he took it. Watch it in the Youtube. Coming soon, in a computer near you

dismissalText.long: c Khurram Manzoor b Wahab Riaz
dismissalText.commentary: Sean Williams c Khurram Manzoor b Wahab Riaz 19 (42b 3x4 0x6 61m) SR: 45.23

dismissalComment.html: Williams could have a misty eye now. He has top-edged a pull shot. It was the short one from Riaz - who has shown a penchant to send that delivery now and then - and Williams' pull went awry. Caught at long-leg. Zimbabwe slid further.

headshotImage.caption: Shoaib Malik player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Shoaib Malik player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Chamu Chibhabha lbw b Shoaib Malik 1 (2b 0x4 0x6 5m) SR: 50

dismissalComment.html: trapped by a quicker one! That one really zipped through. It landed on a length and seamed on straight, Chibhabha was caught completely by surprise and the ball evaded the intended jab and struck him high on the pad. He was on the back foot but the ball looked high. Zaheer Abbas, on air, reckons it would have gone over.

headshotImage.caption: Fawad Alam player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Fawad Alam player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.long: st Sarfaraz Ahmed b Fawad Alam
dismissalText.commentary: Elton Chigumbura st Sarfaraz Ahmed b Fawad Alam 34 (58b 2x4 0x6 73m) SR: 58.62

dismissalComment.html: And it's really bahut aala (very nice) from both the bowler and the 'keeper. Fawad slowed it up, tossed it up a little more, drew the batsman forward before turning it past the bat and Sarfraz did the rest. A useful partnership of 85 runs comes to an end.

headshotImage.caption: Shoaib Malik player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Shoaib Malik player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Brendan Taylor b Shoaib Malik 49 (78b 5x4 0x6 104m) SR: 62.82

dismissalComment.html: Big turn to terminate Taylor's resistance. It pithched a foot outside off stump, Taylor went back and was surprised by the sharp turn that saw the ball rush through his bat and pad. Timber! Just before Malik started his run-up, Sarfraz had chirped, "No 7 No 7  boys"

headshotImage.caption: Shoaib Malik player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Shoaib Malik player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Gary Brent run out (Sarfaraz Ahmed/Shoaib Malik) 4 (5b 0x4 0x6 6m) SR: 80

dismissalComment.html: And then there were two. Mis understanding and a run out. He leaned forward and tapped a ball close on the off side. Yes and no and yes and by that time, Sarfraz had rushed after the ball, thrown his right glove, lunged at the ball and he fired in a throw to Malik.

image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

dismissalText.commentary: Ray Price b Abdur Rauf 7 (14b 1x4 0x6 17m) SR: 50

dismissalComment.html: yorked! Around 130 kmph, full and straight at the off stump, hint of late movement in and Price has a stab and a miss.

headshotImage.caption: Chris Mpofu player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Chris Mpofu player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Chris Mpofu player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Chris Mpofu player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Chris Mpofu b Abdur Rauf 0 (1b 0x4 0x6 1m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: Yorked again! Raufed up! This one swung in a bit more than the previous delivery and went past the jab to crash into the off stump. In a nice gesture, the Pakistani fielders ask Wahab Riaz and Rauf to lead them back to the pavilion.

headshotImage.caption: Keith Dabengwa player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Keith Dabengwa player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Nasir Jamshed c Dabengwa b Chigumbura 19 (18b 2x4 0x6 26m) SR: 105.55

dismissalComment.html: Collision between mid-on and mid-off but the mid-off fielder - Debengwa- holds on to it. It was a slog from Nasir but only managed to send the ball straight up.

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

dismissalText.commentary: Khurram Manzoor b Price 50 (73b 6x4 0x6 105m) SR: 68.49

dismissalComment.html: cleans him up. Right after fifty, he went for a sweep and is gone. It was full and on the off stump, too full to play that hard sweep and it went under the bat and on to the off stump. Price is chuffed up; he really wanted Khurram's wicket, had beaten him on a few occasions. And finally does him in with a straighter one.

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

dismissalText.commentary: Younis Khan c Masakadza b Price 63 (51b 8x4 1x6 70m) SR: 123.52

dismissalComment.html: Masakadza takes a skier. Price went wide of the crease this time, from round the stumps and flighted across a loopy delivery outside off. Younis Khan went down on his knee and attempted a slog-sweep but top edged it towards long-off. Well taken by Masakadza

dismissalText.commentary: Misbah-ul-Haq not out 31 (32b 4x4 1x6) SR: 96.87
